July 18, 2026 — assertions convention standardization (branch: refactor/standardize-assertions-convention)

- Established strict naming rule: `assert*` methods always return `void`/`Promise<void>` (validate + throw only);
  methods that fetch-validate-return an entity use the `find*` or `resolve*` prefix
- Bucket A (converted to void — callers never used the return value):
  categories.assertCategoryExists, admin.assertBookingExists, admin.assertUserExists;
  removed unused return statements and trimmed stale imports
- Bucket B (renamed to find* — callers consume the returned entity):
  bookings.assertBookingExists → findBooking, admin.assertWorkerProfileExists → findWorkerProfile,
  users.assertUserIsActive → findActiveUser, auth.assertUserExistsForRefresh → findUserForRefresh,
  auth.assertRefreshTokenExists → findRefreshToken,
  reviews.assertBookingExistsAndCompleted → findCompletedBooking,
  reviews.assertCustomerProfileExists → findCustomerProfile,
  customers.assertCustomerProfileExists → findCustomerProfile
- Updated all call sites across bookings.service, admin.service, auth.service, reviews.service,
  customers.service, workers.service
- Updated all spec mock objects and describe block names to match new method names
- Updated CLAUDE.md: documented the two-tier assert*/find* convention replacing the old single-tier rule;
  corrected false reference to nonexistent assert.util.ts; noted strike.util.ts as the only real shared util
